<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09155b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09155b">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09155b"> 155(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">A</font> worked right round / village, changing H</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Then they danced like demons for a night and day, the stream of changing partners in this wedding-dance being quite typical of the negro wedding itself, marriage a mere matrimonial dance with constant change of partners. Instead of a garland of orange blossoms, they deserve their appropriate bunch of nettles, &ldquo;bridal&rdquo; being spelt &ldquo;bridle.&rdquo; Of course, this much-married Africa has to pay for all this, the result being daily, disgusting divorce. In one village I found <mark>all the women had worked almost right round the town in wedlock, changing wife being sure of changing husband</mark>. <small> Dan Crawford, <a name="BTLG1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BTLG1"><cite title="source">Back to the Long Grass</cite></a> (1923) 157f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
